<DOCNO> AP881203-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
us authorities have refused to grant refugee 
status to more than 200 soviet jews and armenians but a state 
department official says they could be eligible to enter this 
country through a system known as parole 
state department spokesman charles e redman said friday that the 
wouldbe refugees were unable to demonstrate a wellfounded fear 
of persecution but one way or another he said we continue to 
admit all soviet jewish applicants who choose to come to the united 
states 
the issue was raised by the union of councils for soviet jews 
the private group released two petitions from soviet jews in italy 
awaiting entrance visas to the united states 
most jews who are permitted to leave the soviet union have exit 
permits to emigrate to israel but an overwhelming majority choose 
to go to the united states after they reach rome or vienna 
redman said of more than 4000 applications in rome in october 
and november less than 200 were found not to qualify for refugees 
status but he said if this occurs the applicants are without 
exception given the opportunity to apply for parole 
to be granted parole the us official said applicants must 
show they would be supported by a relative or a sponsor in the event 
jobs were not found the idea is to avoid additional us welfare 
costs 
entering as a refugee provides certain benefits that are not 
available under parole these include transportation expenses some 
support for resettlement and access to medicaid 
in moscow he said 99 applicants most of whom were armenians 
did not qualify for refugee status during the two months but 
redman said they also may seek admission under the parole system 
redman said there was no change in us policy 
the united states continues to call for freedom of emigration 
for all and continues to admit all soviet jewish applicants who 
choose to come to the united states he said most qualify as 
refugees and in addition some enter as parolees 
</TEXT>
