thirteen people filming a documentary 
were trapped more than 250 feet under the ground in a cave today 
after a sudden rainstorm caused the caves mouth to collapse police 
said 
police spokesman rick goodfield said the group was in no 
immediate danger and that rescue workers were trying to reach them 
the rescue team has established a communications line inside 
the cave and they are all doing fine said goodfield the 
nationalities of the film makers were not known 
the group became trapped late friday while filming in the 
extensive cave system under the isolated nullarbor plain in 
southwestern australia goodfield said 
the nullarbor is a huge dry plain but there is an extensive cave 
system underneath it containing subterranean water systems linking 
caves 
peter rogers who left the nullarbor group sunday said they were 
filming a documentary on the caves he said all of those trapped 
were experienced cave divers but that the cave they were in was not 
underwater 
rogers said the group radioed for help from their ground crew 
which in turn notified authorities 
it was a freak hurricane he said you dont get a lot of 
hurricanes on the nullarbor so much water washed down the entrance 
of the cave that it washed enough rubble down to cause a blockage 
about 100 feet down into the cave 
rogers said the group was safely beyond that depth in a large 
chamber about 260 feet below the surface 
no ones injured theyve got communication with the surface 
and theyve got a reasonable amount of water and food rogers said 
