<TEXT>
veteran journalist james henry ferguson 
whose coverage of a 1948 oregon flood for the associated press made 
national headlines died at the age of 72 
ferguson died wednesday of complications following brain surgery 
he began his career in pennsylvania in 1935 as a reporter for the 
dailycourier appeal in dubois 
in 1937 he became editor of the jeffersoniandemocrat in 
brookville pa a weekly newspaper the following year the 
newspaper won five firstplace awards for news editorials and 
feature reporting from the pennsylvania publishers association 
ferguson joined the portland bureau of the associated press in 
1945 three years later he covered the vanport flood in which many 
residents of portlands vanport neighborhood fled their homes when 
the columbia and willamette rivers left their banks 
in 1951 ferguson went to the oregonian as a copy editor he was 
named business editor in the mid1950s 
ferguson also worked as a regional correspondent for mcgrawhill 
publications in 1957 he became news director for pacific power amp 
light co 
he was named an assistant vice president in 1962 and retired in 
1981 
following his retirement he served as chairman of the state 
legislative committee of the american association of retired persons 
and helped win passage of a bill improving the visitation rights of 
grandparents 
a native of new bethlehem pa he attended pennsylvania state 
university and franklin amp marshall college 
</TEXT>
