<TEXT>
chinas breakneck economic development is 
endangering the countrys environment and saddling society with a 
huge cleanup bill the leading paper said saturday 
the peoples daily reported that if forceful policies are not 
implemented the nation faces a future of denuded forests dirty 
lakes barren grasslands and smoggy skies 
the report said the twin evils of pollution and misuse of natural 
resources have reached such a state in china that annual cleanup 
costs are estimated at about 23 billion 
by the end of the century the paper said if the 
environment continues to worsen it will become a major factor 
limiting economic development 
the paper said about 1 percent of the countrys 270 billion 
gross national product or 27 billion should be devoted each 
year to ecology 
but the xinhua news agency reported that by october only 18 
billion had been allocated for the purpose although it said the 
state planned an increase of 50 percent in coming years 
since 1978 chinas gross national product has jumped 100 
percent but the economic and industrial growth has come at an 
enormous ecological cost one which the government has only 
recently begun to realize 
a xinhua report said that by the year 2000 nearly half of 
chinas 2800 lakes could be polluted an earlier survey on 58900 
miles of rivers found that 20 percent were polluted and another 8 
percent seriously contaminated 
reports have blamed acid rain caused by burning the highsulfur 
coal that predominates in china for killing trees in hangzhou a 
beautiful lakeside metropolis south of shanghai 
in the countryside increased use of chemical fertilizers has 
seriously affected soil quality and water resources in addition 
timber poachers who raid forests for firewood and building 
materials have been fingered in the countrys continuing problem 
with deforestation 
the peoples daily said saturdays report was based on a 
fouryear study to forecast environmental conditions in the year 
2000 
the report said that even if forceful policies were adopted 
china would only be able to treat 53 percent of its liquid waste by 
the turn of the century it now treats only about 20 percent of the 
waste 
in addition the study predicted acid rain would continue to 
plague highly industrialized areas and the output of solid waste 
would more than double by 2000 
the report said that damage to farmland accounted for the lions 
share of the annual financial cleanup cost demanding about 97 
billion dollars a year water pollution came next accounting for 
42 billion in damage annually 
third came the financial loss from denuded forests followed by 
air pollution problems caused by chemical fertilizers and the 
destruction of water resources 
</TEXT>
