<TEXT>
soviet citizens got their first look saturday at 
the fine points of a new political system that keeps a tight rein on 
the 15 republics strengthens the presidency and builds a more 
dynamic parliament 
major daily soviet newspapers published details of the reforms 
which were approved thursday by the supreme soviet parliament and 
will go into effect with elections next march 26 
the reforms adopted after five weeks of intense public debate 
attempt to forge a compromise between demands by the republics for 
autonomy and the need for central control by the government in 
moscow 
but a lawyer for a grassroots lithuanian movement scoffed at 
compromises made to the restive republics and said his organization 
was writing a complaint over president mikhail s gorbachevs 
reforms that will arrive at the united nations about the same time 
the soviet leader does 
all the things that choked and are choking us are still 
there kazimieras motieka a member of the governing council of 
the sajudis movement said in a telephone interview from the 
lithuanian capital of vilnius 
the new system establishes a 2250member congress of peoples 
deputies that will include for the first time members of the 
communist party trade union and other organizations as well as 
representatives chosen on the basis of geographical districts and 
ethnic homelands 
the congress will choose a smaller more active supreme soviet 
that is to meet eight months instead of several days a year 
several of the 15 republics especially the baltic republics of 
lithuanian latvia and estonia have complained that the laws as 
proposed by gorbachev in october concentrated too much power in 
moscow 
motieka said the new laws give the national parliament wide power 
over the economy in the republics by including property under the 
jurisdication of the national supreme soviet moscow established 
that what is in our republic is not our property he said 
we cant organize our own agriculture he said we cant 
even change wages 
among the articles changed in the final draft of the reform was 
one opposed by republics because they said it called into question 
their right to secede from the soviet union 
the final version gave the congress of peoples deputies power to 
make decisions on matters of nationalstate structure which are in 
the jurisdiction of the union of soviet socialist republics 
previous language had given it the power to make decisions on 
the composition of the ussr 
the language appeared weaker but motieka contended that the 
change was in words only 
estonia has led opposition to the constitutional changes on nov 
16 its supreme soviet made a declaration of sovereignty in 
internal affairs and proclaimed its right to approve all new 
national laws 
the national government declared that move unconstitutional but 
the estonian parliament meets monday to discuss further expressions 
of autonomy 
the final version of the law gives republics more representatives 
in one of the two houses of the supreme soviet and representation on 
a new constitutional oversight commission 
it orders directives of the central government to be published in 
the languages of the republics 
but it also gives the national presidium specific powers to 
ensure that the constitutions and laws of the republics correspond 
to the national constitution 
gorbachev leaves monday for new york where he will address the 
united nations and meet with president reagan and presidentelect 
george bush he then travels to cuba and britain 
motieka said the governing council of sajudis agreed during a 
session saturday to send a complaint to the united nations a draft 
was being written and a vote would be taken sunday he said 
