<TEXT>
social security commissioner dorcas r hardy 
faced with an outcry over possible changes in disability rules said 
saturday she has rejected the draft proposal that sparked the furor 
she said the draft had generated inaccurate information and 
caused undue alarm to the american public 
she said she remains convinced that the agencys hearings and 
appeals process needs reform but the staffsuggested proposal did 
not meet her criteria of making the system more equitable 
compassionate and efficient 
i believe that ssa the social security administration can do 
better and have therefore rejected it she said in a fourpage 
statement 
the furor erupted last month when the new york times reported the 
reagan administration was considering restricting the right of 
social security applicants to introduce new evidence upon appeal 
thirtyfive senators including one republican dave durenburger 
of minnesota sent a letter to presidentelect george bush on 
wednesday urging him to repudiate the policy change 
hardy in her statement said her agency is deeply committed to 
improving the hearings and appeals process to ensure that claimants 
receive fair timely and accurate decisions when appealing an 
unfavorable government decision 
she said it was important to ensure that the system is 
compassionate since most appeals involve disability claims she 
said people are also entitled to a speedy decision 
the agency gets 300000 requests a year for hearings before its 
800 administrative law judges and it takes an average of nearly two 
years to appeal a claim through the administrative process to the 
federal courts 
hardy said 80 percent of social security beneficiaries now are 
represented at these hearings by lawyers and the agency each year 
pays almost 100 million in fees to attorneys out of the past due 
benefits of claimants who win benefits on appeal 
more than half those who appeal disability denials eventually win 
benefits 
the proposal drafted by the agencys office of hearings and 
appeals would have required claimants to submit all evidence at 
least seven days in advance of a hearing before an administrative 
law judge 
social security officials said the draft had not even reached 
hardys desk when it became public it proved an acute embarrassment 
for hardy often mentioned as a contender for secretary of health 
and human services in the bush administration 
she said that because confidence in our policymaking process 
has been questioned i removed the draft proposal from the routine 
process and personally reviewed it 
disability benefit cutoffs were a major source of controversy in 
the early years of the reagan administration when more than 1 
million disability beneficiaries had their cases reviewed and more 
than 40 percent were ordered off the rolls more than half won on 
appeal and congress and the administration eased up on the reviews 
hardy was not commissioner then 
in her statement hardy said there is nearly unanimous 
agreement that the current hearings and appeals process needs 
reform in addition to our own concerns a vast amount of criticism 
has also come from frustrated claimants attorneys the courts and 
the congress 
to improve it she said we need an open and honest exchange of 
ideas we must explore all options and alternatives 
she said she has asked her disability review council chaired by 
dr john e affeldt to review the hearings and appeals process she 
also invited leaders of congress and all interested parties to 
work together with her to make the process fairer more equitable 
and more responsive to the needs of the american public 
