<TEXT>
president mikhail s gorbachev sets out this week 
on a trip to the united states cuba and britain that will grab 
headlines around the world and may distract some attention from his 
problems at home 
the soviet leader is juggling ethnic violence in the south 
nationalist fever in the baltic republics to the north and a 
pervasive sense that food and other essentials are becoming more 
difficult to find despite his promise that perestroika will make 
life better 
the fires he is trying to control are breaking out at least in 
part because his new tolerance for dissent permits the fanning of 
longsmoldering embers without the harsh policestate crackdowns 
that would have been inevitable here only a few years ago 
at the same time gorbachev is moving ahead with the overhaul of 
the political system that he insists is needed in order to 
institutionalize democracy and block the bureaucracy from sliding 
back into stagnation 
some western diplomats have suggested the soviet presidents 
travels are aimed at bolstering his image as a world leader at a 
time when chronic food shortages and public opposition raise 
questions about the success of his administration at home 
but both soviet and western analysts agree the trip is likely to 
buttress his efforts to integrate the soviet union into the world 
community and advance the improvement in eastwest relations that 
they say is the first step on a long road toward reordering 
domestic priorities in order to divert huge sums now allocated to 
defense and military aid and direct them toward improving the 
quality and availability of goods and services at home 
its reasonable to think that part of the motivation for the 
trip is to polish his image as a leader and effective statesman 
abroad said one western diplomat who studies soviet affairs but 
asked not to be identified the prestige that goes with all of 
that may help him play a role and could cause a certain distraction 
from domestic problems that seem so difficult to move or resolve 
but the western analyst and a soviet foreign affairs specialist 
who also spoke on condition of anonymity agreed that gorbachevs 
trip is consistent with his stated goal of pressing for improved 
relations with the west in order to build and new and better life 
for his people at home 
the soviet union doesnt have the resources to sustain the 
investment its been making in foreign aid and defense the 
diplomat said adding the government must apply those resources to 
domestic problems if gorbachevs reform program which he calls 
perestroika or restructuring is to succeed 
the source noted that western intelligence estimates place soviet 
defense spending at 15 percent to 25 percent of the nations gross 
national product which is at least 25 times the comparable ratio 
spent by the united states 
even the lower end of that range would be enormous by world 
standards the analyst said the upper end would be truly 
staggering 
but beyond the numbers the source added the military now 
monopolizes the nations scientific and technological resources 
leaving the rest of soviet society relatively impoverished and 
unable to pull itself out of its backwardness 
the soviet source in a separate interview said gorbachevs trip 
will be aimed largely at dispelling the image many in the west share 
of the soviet union as an enemy 
we cant afford to finance revolution anymore the source 
said now we must settle these regional conflicts and develop 
friendly relations with those who want to see us at the enemy 
gorbachev only recently disclosed his plan to address the united 
nations say farewell to president reagan and greet george bush 
reagans successor and meet with cuban leader fidel castro and 
british prime minister margaret thatcher 
but he has been extraordinarily active this fall in pressing for 
improved relations particularly with western europe since 
september he has received leaders from west germany austria 
italy romania and france has visited india and on saturday 
discussed with chinas foreign minister the need for a 
sovietchinese summit within the next six months 
hes very much a realist one source said and as a 
realist he knows he must dispel the enemy image and develop a 
network of relationships with other countries before he can permit 
massive reductions in military spending and a reallocation of 
resources 
