despite a distinguished military career seineldin was passed 
over for promotion to brigadier general last year and faced the 
prospect of eventual forced retirement 
he said friday he was not seeking to overthrow argentinas 
constitutional government but to restore military honor to the 
army 
seineldin said he also wanted a review of trials that punish 
the just and promote the guilty it was an apparent reference to 
trials of military officers accused of human rights violations 
during efforts by military governments in the 1970s to put down 
leftist subversion 
seineldin has denied involvement in the disappearance of about 
9000 argentines during the antileftist campaign 
after spending the last four years in panama first as argentine 
military attache and then as an instructor to the panamanian 
national guard seineldin was believed to have returned to argentina 
on thursday via neighboring uruguay to lead the revolt 
he was eager to come home his wife marta alice labiau told the 
private news agency dyn in a telephone interview from panama 
because it was beginning to look like he had been sent into 
exile 
seineldin was born nov 12 1934 in the town of concepcion del 
uruguay 140 miles north of buenos aires his father was a 
businessman and citrus grower 
a graduate of the argentine military academy he rose rapidly in 
rank specializing in infantry commando tactics 
he was assigned to lead commandos on the argentinachile border 
in 1978 when the two neighbors nearly went to war in a dispute over 
three tiny islands 
promoted to colonel seineldin led a commando unit that 
participated in the occupation of the britishheld falkland islands 
on april 2 1982 the argentines who call the islands the malvinas 
were defeated by a british task force 74 days later 
when seineldin was called to testify in human rights abuses 
trials in 1984 troops formerly under his command gathered outside 
the court to cheer him and shouted well go back to the 
malvinas 
