<TEXT>
step into the mysterious windowless 
blue cube where 2000 engineers and scientists working furiously 
with old slow computers will soon have a new task tracking and 
controlling the 500 million spy satellite to be deployed by 
atlantis 
giant screens rows of terminals and bulky machines fill a 
warehousesize room in the militarys ultrasecret satellite 
tracking center receiving millions of bits of coded information 
each second on the location and operation of hundreds of us nato 
and foreign satellites 
the cube can order one of the more than 50 us military 
satellites to snap photos of suspected troop movements and drop off 
the film in a parachute package to an air force plane for a midair 
pickup it can adjust a satellites orbit solar energy panels 
cameras or other gear 
special attention is focused now on the new bird to be placed 
in orbit saturday by the shuttle a radar satellite codenamed 
lacrosse that is designed to spy on the soviet union and guide the 
stealth bomber 
the cube officially called the consolidated space test center 
is run by the air force in the heart of silicon valley next door 
are the nasa ames research center and lockheed missiles amp space co 
inc 
neither journalists nor others without top security clearance are 
allowed past the high fences and armed guards surrounding the pale 
blue building however interviews with air force and nasa officials 
with access to the cube all of whom asked not to be identified 
reveal a beehive of activity as a crack team of physicists 
electrical and mechanical engineers and computer scientists cope 
with a crush of signals to and from satellites 
the adrenalin flows you work 18 hours a day but you dont 
feel tired at all said one veteran of several satellite launches 
you suffer battle fatigue when its over but during the mission 
people get really hyped this is their time and theyre going to 
make it work when you run into obstacles because the system is 
clumsy just sheer energy makes it happen 
the cube has been in operation since 1959 virtually from the 
start of the space program despite the expenditure of several 
hundred million dollars to upgrade the computer and data 
distribution system over the past six years most of the computers 
in the cube are two or three generations old 
they are reliable workhorses built by international business 
machines corp and others in the 1970s and early 1980s but are much 
slower less efficient and more expensive to run than newer models 
at many companies in silicon valley 
instead of state of the art the cubes tubes and software 
programs remain antiquated one systems expert said because of 
government procurement policies 
nasa and the military are stuck in this catch22 the systems 
expert said its hard to sell missions and get money so people 
have to design minimal systems that use equipment from past 
missions and they end up putting systems in place that are terribly 
engineered 
he added though that very exceptional people at nasa and the 
military make the system work despite the system 
until a few years ago the cube was the nations only control 
center for military satellites a place so secret that officials 
used to deny even its existence 
located within bazooka range of two highways and close to three 
earthquake faults the cubes vulnerability led to a 35 billion 
overhaul to bring it up to date and build a command center with 
similar capabilities at falcon air force station in colorado 
springs colo 
those two centers are linked to eight nasa tracking sites around 
the world including guam spain and australia as well as other air 
force stations and a main ground station at white sands nm 
the tracking and data relay satellite system or tdrss is used 
to keep watch over all satellites friendly and unfriendly and any 
other space junk or debris from defunct satellites that could 
get in their way 
tdrss west a satellite in orbit 22000 miles over the western 
united states was the main tracker in space until september when 
the shuttle discovery placed tdrss east in geosynchronous orbit 
22000 miles over the atlantic 
for the launch of the new spy satellite the military and 
civilian teams in the cube and in colorado springs will take over 
control of the satellite from nasa once they get the word the bird 
is in orbit 
because of secrecy requirements nearly all the information from 
the tdrss satellites and the spy satellite is fully encrypted 
the ground station at white sands a huge computer complex that 
is perhaps the most modern communications facility in the world 
receives the information on two bands cband at 56000 bits per 
second and kuband at 300 million bits per second the system can 
run several channels of each band simultaneously taking in a total 
of more than a billion bits of information per second 
the signals are then broken up into multiple channels at lower 
rates easier to handle rebroadcast back up to military satellites 
and down again to the cube and colorado springs where they are 
monitored by the air force round the clock 
the first job after the shuttle drops off the spy satellite is to 
order the firing of positioning rockets to stabilize the satellite 
in orbit 
the exact position and type of orbit are secret although some 
experts call such secrecy a silly game since soviet tracking 
stations can tell where all us satellites are anyway 
